HIV/AIDS: China reports a 14% increase in new cases
China has announced a 14% increase in the number of HIV- and AIDS-affected citizens.
More than 820,000 people suffer from these diseases, according to sources of health authorities.
Approximately 40,000 new cases were reported in the second quarter of 2018.
The vast majority of new cases are due to sexual transmission, which marks a change from the past.
In some regions of China, HIV has spread in the past as a result of infected blood transfusions.
But the number of people who have contracted HIV in this way has been reduced to almost zero, according to what the Chinese health authorities have said during a conference in Yunnan province.
Year after year, however, the number of people with HIV and AIDS in China increased by 100,000 units.
The transmission of HIV by sex is an urgent problem in the Chinese LGBT community.
Homosexuality was decriminalized in China in 1997, but discrimination against LGBT people is still widespread.
Because of the country's traditional values, some studies have estimated that 70% of men who have sex with other men eventually marry women.
Many of the transmissions of diseases are caused by inadequate protections during sexual relations within these relationships.
In 2003, the Chinese government promised universal access to anti-HIV drugs as part of its commitment to managing the problem.
