The opening blows of the trade war between the USA and China were fragrant and, while the battle is still over, experts say that a contrast between the two countries could be beneficial for Beijing in the long term.
Donald Trump, the President of the United States, has already launched the first warning this year by taxing the main Chinese exports, including solar panels, steel and aluminum.
The most significant scaling took place this week with the new duties on articles for more than 200 billion dollars (175 billion euros) of value. This means that taxes will be applied on half of the goods of Chinese origin.
Beijing reacted each time with measures of the same kind by applying duties from five to ten percent on 60 billion US dollars.
China has promised to respond to the US hit and it is unlikely that the second largest economic power in the world will soon march back.
Because Washington resigns, it would be necessary to give in to his demands, but publicly folding in the USA would be too embarrassing for Xi Jinping, the president of China.
However, experts believe that if Beijing plays its cards well, the pressures of trade war with the USA can positively affect China over the long period of time by diminishing the interdependence of the two economies.
\"The fact that a rapid political decision by Washington or Beijing can create the initial conditions of an economic collapse in both countries is in fact much more dangerous than has been recognized so far,\" says Abigail Grace, a researcher who studies Asia at the Center for New American Security Research Center.
Syria is - ready - for the return of refugees, supports the foreign minister
Syria claims to be ready for the return of the refugees and is seeking help to rebuild the country devastated by over seven years of war.
In front of the United Nations General Assembly, Foreign Minister Walid al-Maualem said that the country's conditions are improving.
\"Today the situation on the territory is more stable and secure thanks to the progress made in the fight against terrorism,\" he said.
The government continues to recover areas destroyed by terrorists to restore normalcy.
Now there are all the conditions for the voluntary return of refugees to the country that they had to leave because of terrorism and unilateral economic measures that have affected their daily lives and livelihoods.
According to the United Nations estimate, more than 5.5 million Syrians have left the country since the beginning of the war in 2011.
Another six million people still living in Syria need humanitarian aid.
Al-Moualem stated that the Syrian regime will gladly accept assistance to rebuild the devastated country.
But he pointed out that he would not accept any conditional aid from those countries which supported the insurrection.
