Update on the red tide: the concentration decreases in Pinellas, Manatee and Sarasota
Florida Fish and Wildlife Commission's latest report shows a general decrease in red tide concentration in parts of the Tampa Bay area.
According to the FWC, conditions of chiazze flowering, which suggest a decrease in concentration, are evident in the areas of the county of Pinellas, Manatee, Sarasota, Charlotte and Collier.
The red tide bloom extends for about 130 miles of coastline from the north of the county of Pinellas to the south of the county of Lee.
Chiazze are about 10 miles away from Hillsborough County but in less areas than last week.
The red tide was also observed in Pasco County.
Last week an average concentration was reported in the county of Pinellas or off its coasts, a low to high concentration off the county of Hillsborough, from a bottom concentration to a high concentration in the county of Manatee, from a bottom concentration to a high concentration in the county of Sarasota or off its coast, from a bottom concentration to an average concentration in the county of Charlotte, from a bottom concentration to a high concentration in the county of Lee or off its coast and a low concentration in the county of Collier.
Cases of respiratory irritation continue to be reported in the county of Pinellas, Manatee, Sarasota, Lee and Collier.
While last week no cases were reported in the northwest of Florida.
